segments.text: both as an official employee of A&M, but then after that, a resident of the local community, and one interested in A&M.
What were the factors that helped to make Mr. Rutter such a successful president?
I'll have to go back to it.
When he came here, he called a meeting of all the staff and faculty in Ginehall.
I'll never forget that.
He got up on the stage, and they introduced him and so forth.
He says now, I...
You know and I know I'm not a scholar.
I don't claim to be.
He said, I'm going to be here.
I'm going to do some things that I think can help.
And one of the main things I remember him saying was, he said, I don't understand when we bring freshmen in here, we get into graduate schools.
He said, this is the time of the change in their life.
We need to give them the best we have.
And I think it's one of the greatest things he ever did.
I agree.
But now, I don't think the war, his war,
action had much to do with it.
Most people didn't know about it.
He was just a man's man, I think.
He would talk to anybody.
You know this.
He'd just visit with you.
I wrote him a note.
We had one time Texas University threatened to come over here and break up our final review.
And I was at that time with Stallings, worked coaching with Coach Stallings.
This was 1969, 70.
And I went down to
he just he just a fine guy that he did not feel like he was superior to anybody but he knew he could do anything right now you left the university officially and then came back
Yeah.
In 1970, Stallings, who was coaching me, asked me to come back on his staff as the recruiting partner.
Okay.
And I came back and stayed with him until he got fired.
All right.
Let's talk about those years.
Okay.
How had the NM changed in 1970 from what you remembered it?
Well, again, like I said, I stayed on the campus half the time, and it was just like I'd never left.
That's what's so strange.
I never left the campus even though I wasn't on the payroll.
I was over there playing handball or talking or stuff all the time.
But now we had women by then.
We had the women, and I was definitely against women.
My daughter, who's 50 years old now, she could not go to Texas A&M because of girls.
And I think it's true, and you know that when they took it to the Supreme Court three times, we had women, and I didn't like that.
My wife, my present wife, both her daughters were graduates of Texas A&M, and her son-in-law was a graduate of Texas A&M.
I think it's probably the greatest thing that ever happened to us.
But it was the idea of having girls on this campus we just couldn't buy.
And I say publicly, and I'll stand on the front porch of the MSC, that I think the girls have a whole lot better attitude than the boys.
You walk across that campus and see his feet.
Yes.
And you watch some of these jokers, men that are going to take the A&M.
I'm embarrassed.
Like you said a while ago, you thought he got too big.
I agree with you.
When I interviewed Speaker Clayton about his student days, he told me that he had been a strong opponent of coeducation.
And I said, well, sir, why?
And he said, because I thought the girls would kill the spirit.
And then he stopped and he said, do the girls have Aggie spirits?
And I then, about what you just said, I said, sir, I believe that they have even more pride than the boys do.
And he brightened up and he said, good, good.
Then he started telling me how many of his nieces and granddaughters and so forth.
I wish she could.
I wish Pauline could have gone to Texas.
Thank you, thank you.
Now, of course, that's the big change there, I guess.
The big change to me is the size of it.
And we've got, what, 40,000, 42,000.
We've got 2,000 courts.
But you talk to people away from here, in your place in Missouri or North Carolina, they still think so.
Because that's what they see on television.
That's what they see on the TV ads.
Let's see.
Back to those Stallings days.
Describe Gene Stallings as the football coach then.
Okay.
Frankly, I do not remember James Stallings playing football with Brad Bryant.
He was all conference and all.
But he wasn't, at least of course John David stole everything.
But I went, when Stallings first came back, I refereed football at Southwest Conference for 25 years.
And lots of times, we local officials would go down and work the scrimmage games for the Aggies when Bryant was here and all those guys.
And I got to know Stallings out there
officiating the scrimmages.
And one day, we had a play, and I called the pass interference, and he came charging me, just maddering away at him, because I called him.
And I said, look, coach, you want me to call Mike Dower, or do you want me to call him?
He said, you're proud of your job, but I'm proud of mine, too.
And I've got pride in my job, and I'm going to call this game.
If you don't want me, I'll leave right now.
Well, I thought, I know that guy, too.

after that practice I was walking off he came over and put his arm in my shoulder it wasn't two weeks later that he sent one of his assistant coaches to see if I could work with him so when he came to jump on you this is when you were coaching I mean when he was the head coach I was officiating and I wasn't scared of him at all because I'd seen about ten other coaches come through and I learned to love that man as much as I ever loved a man so I went to work for him and
He was a funny old boy.
I'll tell you off of his thinking stories, but I won't tell you because I don't want to break it.
All right, let's see.
Now, who were the key members of his staff?
Well, Elmer Smith was his assistant coach.
He hired Elmer Smith to come down here and coach.
Elmer had been coaching up in Arkansas.
And then he had B. Powell, who had played with him, and a guy named Bobby.
Jimmy Bryant.
He had a guy named Lloyd Taylor who's still here in college.
He had a guy from over here at Franklin.
A lot of his staff were played with him.
Pauline, where's that picture of that coaching thing, honey?
Let me see that.
I can't remember some of those guys.
I've got a picture.
And he was...
His staff was comparatively young.
They were all young except Elmer, and Elmer was an old man.
But Elmer had coached with Barry Bryant when he was here.
And Barry Bryant left, went back home to Alabama, and Elmer went with him.
Elmer wasn't happy there.
He felt he made a mistake.
So he came back, and he stayed with Paul Schmeier, Jim Meyers.
And then when Elmer stayed with Fulberg here.
And then, of course...
Elmer told me, he said, Gene called him when he got the job.
He said, Elmer, you come with me.
We're going to have a dynasty at Texas A&M.
Let me look here and see if I can see those guys.
Now, in terms of...
Here's that coaching staff right here.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Right here.
The...
He ran the same, did he run by and large the same offense and defense that Bryant had run?
Yeah, I guess.
I wasn't that familiar with that.
Let me tell you about this stuff.
Bear Bryant, Coach Bear Bryant, when he was at Texas A&M, he wore work shoes and he wore long khaki pants to practice.
Stallings wore work shoes and long khaki pants.
Stallings would not let any of his coaches wear shorts.
on the practice field.
Bryant didn't like it.
I don't know how close Stalin tried to ape or mimic Bryant.
Everybody says that because I didn't know Bear Bryant that well.
But I don't know.
They keep saying that's what hurt him.
I'll tell you what hurt him, but I won't tell you on that thing.
All right, let's go back to Bryant.
because you observed Bryant up pretty close.
Who selected Bryant to be the head coach?
Okay, Mr. Penberthy was dean of, was head of the athletic council, and it was the athletic council's job to fire and hire the coach.
Mr. Penberthy told me, he says, when the prior coach left.
Norton?
No, it was the second, and then the next one.
But anyway, Mr. Penny, Mr. Penberthy said that he and his group were interviewing people like Blair at Army.
They interviewed Oklahoma Coast.
He said, we interviewed everybody we could.
We didn't expect to get them, but when the word came out, why didn't you ask old Joe?
Why didn't you ask him?
We did.
And he says, I pick up the paper and lo and behold, I see that Barry Bryant's been hired by the Board of Regents, Board of Directors.
Was there, as far as you know, was there a particular board member?
I don't even know who it was.
At that time, I probably did, but I don't recall who it was.
Not like when Bob Bryant hired you.
Did...
What was his first venture here?
How did he arrive?
He came in like a hurricane.
He later said that he had heard that if you let the Aggies get too close to you, they'll stab you in the back.
So he shut down all observation.
He put a fence up where nobody could watch practice.
My office at that time was in DeWare.
And here came guys that I had known.
driving up in the big Cadillac, they would park and come into my office, because they were kind of same age as me, and say, do you think, Coach, I can see Coach?
They were even afraid to go down and try and see, because his office was on the west side of Kyle Field, up under the stands there, where the dressing room was on the other side.
And one time, or several times, they'd go in there, and he'd say, did you bring me a crossbar?
No, Coach, you bring me a crossbar, he won't come back to me.
Everybody was scared to death.
And he was in his 40s?
40ish?
Yeah, he was a young man.
Describe him physically.
I'd say he was probably 6'2", but in most people's minds, he was about 6'10".
And he was a well-built old boy.
I've got a picture of him in there somewhere.
At that time, the MSC was the main hangout.
Well, you were here.
No.
Yeah.
The hangout for coffee time.
Everybody would go to coffee at the MSC.
Maybe.
Bryant walked in there.
You go to a cafe, you go to a hotel, you go anywhere, and I'll swear that 99% of the conversations were about Bear Bryant every day.
He dominated this place.
You've heard the expression, he walks in the room and draws attention.
Bryant walked like John Wayne.
He walked in the room and drew attention and never said a word.
Right now, he came early in the calendar year
You know, soon after football season's over.
And that first year, he had really good recruiting success in bringing in lots of freshmen.
About 19 out of the top 20.
I'll tell you a story about that.
And then he took the varsity.
He didn't take freshmen.
He took the varsity to Junction, didn't he?
Yes.
Okay.
Go ahead.
Well, during the first year, he was 1-11, I think.
And towards the end of the year, he just quit the varsity and took all of his freshmen.
There's a story that Colonel Frank Anderson told me.
Frank Anderson was track coach at Texas Indian for 48 years.
He came here in the teens with Mr. Bible as assistant coach with Mr. Bible.
He and Mr. Bible were like brothers.
Mr. Bible left and went to Nebraska, then came to Texas.
Colonel Anderson told me that all the athletic directors got together one time in Austin with the intent of getting this done.
Mr.

Colonel Andy said, Mr. Bible walks in this room, Mr. Bible from Texas walks in this room and says to these other athletes, gentlemen, it's my understanding and order to leave a fellow member of the Southwest Conference.
It must be unanimous.
Is that being the case?
And I'll contend that what you said, Texas University is the best university in the world.
I agree with that.
Nobody like, nearly hated him.
Well, because he got old football players.
He bought them all.
No question about that.
He bought John David.
He bought Lloyd Paley.
He bought everything inside.
Describe what you know about the Junction.
Or what everybody else knows.
They went down there and two came back and won.
I've heard scholars talk about it.
I have a good friend named Dave Smith.
Dave Smith is the only guy that went to Junction and left that became a head football coach later.
Now, he took the sophomores, juniors, and seniors, not the freshmen.
I didn't know that.
Well, I'm guessing.
I don't know.
And a whole bunch of them dropped out.
Well, it said, Dolly said in his little pocket, they went down in two buses and came back in one.
What the guys told me, some of them that I talked to that left, they said we would leave at night.
We'd crawl out the window and go to the highway and hitchhike to get out of there.
And none of them had the
I wouldn't have had either to go to Mr. Bryant and say, Coach, I can't handle this.
I'm leaving.
They'd be afraid to see me.
But they just snuck off.
And as you look back on it, do you think that most people believe that he deliberately wanted to drive some of those people off?
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know why he took them.
He said in one of his books I read, he said he'd never do that again.
Because he didn't do it but once did.
Yeah, yeah.
I don't think it panned out exactly.
And didn't he lose some good prospects?
Probably did.
Probably lost a lot of people.
He said, I'm not going to put stuff to that.
You couldn't do it today.
Yeah.
Oh, no way.
No, no.
They probably lost six.
If you talk to the guys that stayed and they think it's fantastic, the guys that left, they're ashamed.
Yeah.
So I don't know.
All right.
In the years that he was here, did he continue to be that kind of removed, separate person?
He would not.
That's what I know of it.
He would not talk to anybody.
The only friend he had, good, close friend, this guy's got this student factory out here, 121, big tag.
He had a big home down north of Miami.
Whatever that is.
But Bryant did not.
Bryant did not.
Willie Zappalack was assistant coach, and Willie and I played together.
He kept Willie Zappalack on the staff.
Ray George was the guy that was for him.
He was the only one that he kept, and he kept Willie because Willie's been an Aggie.
He had connections with former students in that league for him.
And Willie said that if they went on these tours, they'd be going for five weeks.
And he said at night, he'd go to his room at night.
He said, I had very little personal contact with him.
Every one of his coaches kept a, I understand, they kept a bag packed in the office.
He'd say, Barney, won't you go talk to him?
He was a very demanding man, but I think the guys respected him.
He could be mean.
Yeah, Bernath.
Oh, yeah, Bernath Concrete.
That's right.
And they were big buddies.
B-E-R-N-A-T-S.
I think that's the only great friend he had.
And there was a guy at the North Gate that had a...
I guess it was a restaurant that he'd go by there every morning and they'd call him.
And let's see.
During those years, Morgan was president part of those years, and then he left, so there was no strong administrative...
authority like there would be with Rudder and later with Jack Williams.
Let me tell you something.
Here's what happened.
You know the name Jones Ramsey.
Is this going to happen?
You're going to edit this.
Wait, wait, wait.
Let me turn this off.
I said, no, sir, I don't want you to do that.
I wasn't about to have you get off.
This is the first thing.
We've got a Saturday football game, and I get blamed for it.
Well, thereafter, any time they had games scheduled in the office of G. Ronnie White, they would have a bunch of basketball where I used my footballs.
He would have one of his coaches call me and ask me.
Well, I was about to say no, but I did appreciate him calling me and asking me.
He didn't step on little people.
He just squashed big people, I guarantee you.
Now, I've heard that Jerry Claiborne was the coach and member of the coaching staff who went to the faculty to talk about grades and so forth.
Is that right?
As you understand, is that correct?
I don't know.
I knew Jerry real well, but we played handball all the time.

What I heard was that he would come to chat with them, that he was always very, very thoughtful, always very conscientious, always very kind, patient, and that quite often, as he would be chatting, he would check his watch, and he'd pull his pocket watch out,
he would always flip his Phi Beta Kappa key.
I don't know about that.
Where they could see it.
But he was a heck of a nice guy.
And that he always gave them a very nice, positive impression, and that there was no high-handedness, that they got any impression of high-handedness from Coach Clayton.
Yeah, yeah.
Chris Brown, you know him?
Sure, sure.
He told me that...
He says, I said before Bryant came here, he says he's not going to run me.
He was sharing that with me.
He's not going to run me.
And he came on Bryant's biggest performance.
He'd done anything Bryant.
Bryant just charmed him to death.
And Bryant did not.
You talk to people and tell me one time that Bryant never talked to anybody.
When they'd go recruit, Bryant didn't recruit.
He just sat there.
He just did it by osmosis, I guess.
But he let other people build up his reputation.
Now, were folks like you aware that he was about to leave?
No.
That was a complete lie.
Well, let me back off.
We thought that he was having trouble here because of recruiting.
Mm-hmm.
I think I was surprised when he says, when Mother calls, when you come back to Alabama.
And there was mixed emotions about it, I think.
Okay.
All right, let's go back then now and do your student days.
Okay.
We're not freshmen.
Let's see.
You were telling me about why you came here in the first place.
How did you get to College Station for that first visit?
Darius Mosher.
Darius Mosher's parents lived in Stephenville.
I had never heard of Texas A&M until I was in high school.
You know, I'd heard of it, but I didn't think about it.
But I loved Darius Mosher like a big brother to me, and I'd never seen a big football game.
I had gone to Fort Worth to see Sammy Ball, some old people play.
But they brought me down here several times when we would come to watch A&M play, and I'd stay over in the dorm with a guy named Cecil Ballew,
who played baseball here, who was later dean of men at Crawford State University.
And I'd come down to them, and I came to A&M and watched some football games, and I got where I could tell each player just by the way he walked.
You can't do that today.
But they had some individual deals about them.
So when I was being recruited by several schools, and I didn't know what to do, and
I went to Rice because they recruited me strongly and actually a guy had offered me some help that his brother-in-law was mayor of Stephenville at that time.
And so I went down there but it didn't turn out so I came back up here.
The first time I just came down was Derrick Moser's parents.
Right and so and you enrolled in the fall of?
41 and A&M's football program was very, very, very strong then.
Yeah we won the conference that year and had won it.
39 were the champions.
40, they won it in 41.
But in 38, they nearly got fired.
If it hadn't been for Bert Clopper, it would have been, because he came to take care of, he wasn't at the time, because he was Martin's big boss.
Okay.
What was your, when you visited the campus first, what was your impression of the people you encountered?
I was so scared to death my freshman year.
I don't remember much, but
I don't know that it was any different than anywhere else.
I don't know.
Most of the guys at that time were 60% or more of the boys would take them and work with them through school.
Yeah, but did you think that this, when your first impression, did you think this was a friendly place?
Yes, definitely.
And the one thing that made it friendly, I think, was uniform.
We had Jewish boys, we had Catholic boys, we had Protestant boys, we had rich boys, we had poor boys, but everybody was the same.
The uniform leveled it out.
I didn't have anything.
My parents didn't have anything like most kids did.
But we were well off the next day.
And I have understood, after chatting with people like you and so forth and hearing the recollections, that those differences of background of religion, ancestry, and money
almost vanished, you were, once you put on that uniform, once you became a member of the group.
Yeah, you were an Aggie.
And everybody got a nickname.
What was your nickname?
Well, I always went Barney.
Barney is a nickname.
Oh, it is?
Okay.
What is your?
Fowler Barnett, B-A-R-N-E-T. Oh, Fowler Barnett.
Fowler was my mother's maiden name.
My first wife's father was a farmer, and he probably never saw an athletic contest in his life.
Okay.
And he was listening on the radio when I came down here, and they called me Fowler Wells.
And he asked his daughter, he says, why is Barney Fowler so much?
And I didn't know my name was Fowler until I got down here with the first tip.
But I didn't have a nickname.
Share with the machine some of the distinctive nicknames that you recall of either friends or Aggie nicknames of friends or faculty or anybody.
I wish I had that.
Pauline, where's that list I picked up one time?
One time at our meeting, this meeting.
I sat down and wrote down every faculty guy that I could think of.
Let me give you these.
Okay, first of all, there was Bigfoot Jackson.
These are faculty.
Did he have big feet?
I guess, I don't know.
Wheezy Clark.
You know Wheezy Clark?
Wheezy Clark was the guy.
Let's go back to when Mr. Gilchrist was a civil engineer.
There's a place over here called Billy Goat Bridge, right across from Pat Olsen's home.
You know that lake?
Pat, Mr. Gilchrist, had a city connection.
He made them drain it because of Skeeter.
Wheezy Clark had developed all that land.
And that was the cause of that big rebellion and
20 years later over on the campus.
Because Wheezy Clark and Mr. Bryan, Travis Bryan, hated Barry Bryan.
I mean, Mr. Gilkins.
Wheezy because he messed up on that play.
And Mr. Bryan because when he built the College Station State Bank, Gilkins started putting money in there and taking Mr. Bryan.
And they two instigated that thing with a guy named Sam Williams who was a student and a football player.
And they're the guys that started that whole mess.
Orster Joe Gammon.
Gammon, yes, because he'd clear his throat.
Big Track Buck.
Notes Dance.
Yes.
Head End Jones.
Steppin' Half Hedges.
Screamin' Al Nelson.
I had him in class.
I know what he was.
Jumpin' Jim Potter.
Jim Potter.
Oh.
Dusty Colford.
Mm-hmm.
Cube Foot, Cube Root Kent.
Cube Root Kent.
Cube Root Kent.
And Square Root Jackson.
Yeah.
Blue Brook Benton.
Camp Basie, I don't know who that is.
Dan the man, Dan the great point man, Dan Russell.
Not Dan, Dr. Dan Russell.
Dr. Dan, I had him in classes, yeah.
Cigar Davis.
But those were Smokey, now these are guys that I think were really ought to be settled.
Bear Bryant, Smokey Harper, Dr. Dobbs, Ivy League Taylor.
You remember him?
He gave Stallings more to pay off.
And he and I used to play tennis.
You know, he'd press the tennis player one time.
But he'd come up in the stands when we'd work now in college.
He'd sit up there with his shirt off.
And Stallings would pick it up for Grandma.
He wouldn't leave.
He was a faculty prop.
Stallings hated that guy because he would go, oh, love, oh, love.
Taylor would egg him on, and I understand he turned out to be one of those people.
Nick Callahan, Bull Boatman, remember Boatman?
Jocko Robertson, Jock Woods.
These are some names we picked up.
All right, what about some of your buddies, your classmates?
Well, I'm trying to think.
Most of them, let's see.
Okay, Whiskey Cure.
Let's get to Cure.
Wayne Cure was a guy who played football at Tarleton, and they claimed he kept a little pint in his little pocket up there on his shirt, and he'd stick it through a straw.
And I played with him, Wayne Cure, and gosh, I can't think.
Let's see.
All right, let me.
I can't think of those guys.
All right, were there any?
Bill Henderson, Boots Henderson.
Did the Jewish kids have a nickname?
I don't know.
Hispanic?
No.
I don't think they mean Hispanic either.
Okay.
Fat guys?
Short guys?
Jelly Steinman was an old boy from over here at Blastrop.
Later he was a colonel and he was a fat boy, Jelly Steinman.
And...
Hank Goldberg was his nickname, his name was Henry.
Of course, Buddy Denton was that dude.
Do you agree with me that these nicknames, in fact, were terms of endearment?
Yes, definitely were.
They may have been kind of backhanded.
Okay, your freshman year, where did you live?
I lived over, the athletes lived together my freshman year, and we lived in dorm 12.
over in what is now the court area.
Did you have what we now call a scholarship?
Yes, we had a full scholarship.
We got room, board, bus, tuition, and $5 a month for London.
Okay.
And then about how much more money did you spend a month?
My parents would send me $5 a month.
Oh, so $5 more.
Yeah.
Okay.
Yeah.
And you came, that first fall, you arrived about what date?
Probably 1st or 2nd.
So football practice started about that?
We started practice immediately.
And how many freshmen were there on the team?
About 110.
But there weren't that many on scholarship?
Oh, no, no, no.
And do you remember the routine of the first workouts?
I remember the routine of everything.
First of all, we would never go in the dressing room to the
upperclassmen had left.
Never.
Because they'd get up there and beat our butts.
And the coaches would sit there and watch you.
And we would stay on the field until the upperclassmen had cleaned up and left and gone.
But unfortunately, we all went back to the same dormitory.
I cleaned up a room for a guy named Darius Moser, who's a dear friend of mine.
And Jim... My routine every morning, I'd get up
And I'd go up and clean their tunes.
I'd shine their shoes.
And unfortunately, one of them wanted to get up and one of them didn't.
And so I'd have to wake one of them up and not wake the other up.
I was going to get my butt beat the other way.
Then I would take their laundry out and I would go over in the mess hall and bring the breakfast to them back and do it.
Now that was every morning we did that.
Was that kind of common?
Oh, everybody, they had every upper class had room order.
Well, I know that, but that bringing the meal back.
If they wanted, you did what they wanted.
And we just understood that's what you're supposed to do.
Okay.
Classes didn't begin until late in September.
Did you all have two-a-day workouts?
Yes, we worked out two days.
And the head coach was Homer Norton.
Homer Norton.
Describe Coach Norton as a person.
Well, Coach Norton as a fiscal or otherwise?
Coach Norton was a very aloof man to me.
Now, to some people he was not, but he did not, I think if he saw me on the street, he wouldn't know who I was.
Never spoke to him, I don't guess.
On the field, it was different.
But I found out later that Coach Norton, his last year, this was, of course, a freshman, he didn't have any good management.
